5 A BILL
6 TO BE ENTITLED
7 AN ACT
8
9 Relating to corporations, partnerships, and
10 associations; to designate Sections 10A-17-1.01 through
11 10A-17-1.18, Code of Alabama 1975, inclusive, as Article 1;
12 and to add Article 2, commencing with Section 10A-17-2.01, to
13 Chapter 17 of Title 10A of the Code of Alabama 1975; to
14 provide for the formation, management, and governance of
15 decentralized unincorporated nonprofit associations; to
16 provide for the duties, obligations, and liabilities of
17 members and administrators of decentralized unincorporated
18 nonprofit associations; and to provide for the dissolution and
19 winding up of decentralized unincorporated nonprofit
20 associations.
21 BE IT ENACTED BY THE LEGISLATURE OF ALABAMA:
22 Section 1. Sections 10A-17-1.01 through 10A-17-1.18,
23 Code of Alabama 1975, inclusive, are designated as Article 1.
24 Section 2. Article 2, commencing with Section
25 10A-17-2.01, is added to Chapter 17 of Title 10A of the Code
26 of Alabama 1975, to read as follows:
27 §10A-17-2.01
28 This article together with applicable provisions of
Page 1

This article together with applicable provisions of
SB277 Engrossed
29 Chapter 1 shall be known and may be cited as the Decentralized
30 Unincorporated Nonprofit Association Law.
31 §10A-17-2.02
32 For the purposes of this article, the following terms
33 have the following meanings:
34 (1) ADMINISTRATOR. A person authorized by the members
35 of a decentralized unincorporated nonprofit association to
36 fulfill administrative or operational tasks at the direction
37 of the membership.
38 (2) DECENTRALIZED UNINCORPORATED NONPROFIT ASSOCIATION
39 or NONPROFIT ASSOCIATION. An unincorporated nonprofit
40 association that meets the following requirements:
41 a. Consists of at least 100 members joined by mutual
42 consent in digital activity under an agreement, which may be
43 in writing or inferred from conduct, for a common nonprofit
44 purpose, including, but not limited to, administering the
45 affairs of a distributed ledger technology or network of smart
46 contracts.
47 b. Has elected to be formed under this article.
48 c. Is not formed under any other law governing the
49 nonprofit association's organization or operation.
50 (3) DIGITAL ASSET. A representation of economic,
51 proprietary, or access rights that is stored in a computer
52 readable format and is either a digital consumer asset,
53 digital security, or virtual currency.
54 (4) DISTRIBUTED LEDGER TECHNOLOGY. A distributed ledger
55 protocol and supporting infrastructure, including blockchain,
56 which uses a distributed, shared, and replicated ledger,
Page 2

which uses a distributed, shared, and replicated ledger,
SB277 Engrossed
57 whether public or private, permissioned or permissionless, and
58 which may include the use of digital assets as a medium of
59 electronic exchange.
60 (5) ESTABLISHED PRACTICES. The practices used by a
61 decentralized unincorporated nonprofit association without
62 material change during the most recent five years of the
63 nonprofit association's existence, or if the nonprofit
64 association has existed for less than five years, during the
65 nonprofit association's entire existence.
66 (6) GOVERNING PRINCIPLES. All agreements and any
67 amendment or restatement of those agreements, including any
68 decentralized unincorporated nonprofit association agreements,
69 consensus formation algorithms, smart contracts, or enacted
70 governance proposals, which govern the purpose or operation of
71 a decentralized unincorporated nonprofit association and the
72 rights and obligations of the nonprofit association's members
73 and administrators, whether contained in a record, implied
74 from the nonprofit association's established practices, or
75 both.
76 (7) MEMBER. A person who, under the governing
77 principles of a decentralized unincorporated nonprofit
78 association, may participate in the selection of the
79 decentralized unincorporated nonprofit association's
80 administrators or the development of the policies and
81 activities of the decentralized unincorporated nonprofit
82 association.
83 (8) MEMBERSHIP INTEREST. A member's voting rights in a
84 decentralized unincorporated nonprofit association determined
Page 3

decentralized unincorporated nonprofit association determined
SB277 Engrossed
85 by the decentralized unincorporated nonprofit association's
86 governing principles, including as ascertained from
87 decentralized ledger technology on which the decentralized
88 unincorporated nonprofit association relies to determine a
89 member's voting rights.
90 (9) NONPROFIT PURPOSE. Any purpose for which a
91 nonprofit corporation could be organized under Article 1, and
92 where no part of income or profit is distributable to its
93 members or administrators.
94 (10) PERSON. An individual, corporation, business
95 trust, estate, trust, partnership, association, agency, joint
96 venture, government, governmental subdivision or
97 instrumentality, or any other legal commercial entity.
98 (11) RECORD. Information that is inscribed on a
99 tangible medium or stored in an electronic or other medium
100 that is retrievable in perceivable form.
101 (12) SMART CONTRACT. An automated transaction, as
102 defined in any substantially similar analogue or code, script,
103 or programming language relying on distributed ledger
104 technology, including blockchain, which may include
105 facilitating and instructing transfers of an asset,
106 administrating membership interest votes with respect to a
107 decentralized unincorporated nonprofit association, or issuing
108 executable instructions for these actions based on the
109 occurrence or nonoccurrence of specified conditions.
110 (13) STATE. A state of the United States, the District
111 of Columbia, the Commonwealth of Puerto Rico, or any territory
112 or insular possession subject to the jurisdiction of the
Page 4

or insular possession subject to the jurisdiction of the
SB277 Engrossed
113 United States.
114 §10A-17-2.03
115 (a) The law of this state governs any decentralized
116 unincorporated nonprofit association that is formed in this
117 state.
118 (b) Each decentralized unincorporated nonprofit
119 association's governing principles shall identify the
120 jurisdiction in which the decentralized unincorporated
121 nonprofit association is formed.
122 §10A-17-2.04
123 (a) A decentralized unincorporated nonprofit
124 association may engage in profit-making activities. Profits
125 from any activities shall be used in furtherance of, or set
126 aside for, the nonprofit association's common nonprofit
127 purpose.
128 (b) Except as provided in subsection (c), a
129 decentralized unincorporated nonprofit association may not
130 make distributions to its members or administrators.
131 (c) A decentralized unincorporated nonprofit
132 association may do all of the following:
133 (1) Pay reasonable compensation or reimburse reasonable
134 expenses to its members, administrators, and persons outside
135 of the nonprofit association for services rendered, including
136 with respect to the administration and operation of the
137 nonprofit association, which may include the provision of
138 collateral for the self-insurance of the nonprofit
139 association, voting, or participation in the nonprofit
140 association's operations and activities.
Page 5

association's operations and activities.
SB277 Engrossed
141 (2) Confer benefits on its members and administrators
142 in conformity with its common nonprofit purpose.
143 (3) Repurchase membership interests to the extent
144 authorized by the nonprofit association's governing
145 principles.
146 (4) Make distributions of property to members upon
147 winding up and termination of the decentralized unincorporated
148 nonprofit association to the extent permitted by Section
149 10A-17-2.26.
150 §10A-17-2.05
151 (a) Unless prohibited or otherwise limited by its
152 written rules or governing documents, a decentralized
153 unincorporated nonprofit association in its name may acquire,
154 hold, encumber, or transfer an estate or interest in real or
155 personal property.
156 (b) Unless prohibited or otherwise limited by its
157 written rules or governing documents, a decentralized
158 unincorporated nonprofit association may be a legatee,
159 devisee, or beneficiary of a trust or contract.
160 (c) Real and personal property in Alabama may be
161 acquired, held, encumbered, and transferred by a decentralized
162 unincorporated nonprofit association, whether it or a member
163 has any other relationship to Alabama.
164 §10A-17-2.06
165 (a) A decentralized unincorporated nonprofit
166 association shall execute and record a statement of authority
167 to transfer an estate or interest in real property in the name
168 of the nonprofit association.
